<div id="review_2565021252" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2565021252" />
    <a title="Hind" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53631178-hind"><img alt="Hind" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603372021p2/53631178.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2565021252?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hind" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hind" href="/user/show/53631178-hind">Hind</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2565021252" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1481513310400050498">Sonny&apos;s Blues is a story about a plethora of things, among which is arrant purgatory, unarticulated suffering, ire, and the ceaseless scuffle life shoves down our throats until it rubs so rawly it atrociously hurts.<br/><br/>It is a story about drug addiction and the relationship betwixt a musician&apos;s life, mind, and instrument. Nevertheless, to me, it was a story of the artist as a sufferer before anything else, for as an artist, too—or let us say a human who is struggling—I can only entangle and unweave </span>
  <span id="freeText1481513310400050498" style="display:none">Sonny's Blues is a story about a plethora of things, among which is arrant purgatory, unarticulated suffering, ire, and the ceaseless scuffle life shoves down our throats until it rubs so rawly it atrociously hurts.<br /><br />It is a story about drug addiction and the relationship betwixt a musician's life, mind, and instrument. Nevertheless, to me, it was a story of the artist as a sufferer before anything else, for as an artist, too—or let us say a human who is struggling—I can only entangle and unweave my threads of anguish through words I truly have a love and loathe relationship with.<br />My words unclothe my being; they make me vulnerable, they make me cognisant of my suffocating agony, aware of all that I constantly want to abscond from, and most of all, it makes me realise that my efforts in escaping this absurd reality will for aye fail, that trying to settle at ease is unduly far out of my reach. Yet, my words also palliate me from the sickness I call life, they assuage all the feelings I'm left with after tumultuously oscillating from eternal states of darkness into epheremal states of relief by allowing me to express what I feel in writing—just like Sonny was only able to speak truly when his digits fought and made love to those ivory white and black keys of an instrument which is a vessel of the soul of the artist playing it. It was as if Baldwin was telling me that every artistic expression from every artist could be a portal through which one can see all the beauties, scars, trepidations, and agonies. <br /><br />Sonny's Blues was a story overwhelmed with emotions and its characters were keys that unlocked hidden doors within me. As I read it whilst soft jazz played and my cat drifted to slumber next to me, I remembered an abundance of things, and one of those, thanks to this book, was the first time I've shed tears whilst one of my favorite jazz players spoke to me through his music. <br /><br />This had turned into a vent of some sort; however, I'm grateful that I've gotten all those feelings from reading a short story, and now I cannot wait to delve deeper into his lengthier works.<br /><br />Today, yours truly had lost her Baldwin virginity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1481513310400050498" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


